<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CREAM SKIMMING</ENAMEX>
Volumes, revenues and route profits differ widely on routes in
both <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Italy</ENAMEX> and the
<ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">U.S.</ENAMEX> The uniform pricing constraint of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">USO</ENAMEX> creates cream
skimming possibilities because an entrant can target only highly
profitable routes and charge a price below the uniform price.
Consequently, it is not cross-subsidy per se that allows cream
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">skimming</ENAMEX>. All routes could be <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">above</NUMEX> incremental cost and the
problem would still exist. <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">Cream</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">skimming</ENAMEX> stems from the uniform
pricing and service constraints given that routes have disparate
profits, and not necessarily from the need to cross-subsidize
routes.
